<dl>
<dt>Project Title</dt><dd>Simple Decision-Making</dd>
<dt>Principal Investigator</dt><dd>Kodi B. Arfer, PhD</dd>
</dl>

<p><strong>You are being asked to be a volunteer in a research study.</strong>

<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>The purpose of this study is to understand how people make decisions. Results will increase our understanding of how people decide between two alternatives in a variety of settings.

<h2>Procedures</h2>
<p>If you decide to be in this study, your part will involve pressing keys on your device's keyboard to indicate which of various options you prefer. There may be multiple conditions to which you may be assigned.  If so, you will be assigned to your condition randomly (by chance).

<h2>Risks / Discomforts</h2>
<p>There are no foreseeable risks or discomforts associated with your participation in this study.

<h2>Benefits</h2>
<p>There is no benefit expected as a result of your being in this study.

<h2>Compensation</h2>
<p>There is a reward of money assigned to the Human Intelligence Task (HIT) you have accepted. You will receive this reward after completing the HIT provided that you did not attempt the experiment more than once (even if the same experiment is associated with multiple HITs).

<h2>Confidentiality (Protecting Your Privacy in this Study)</h2>
<p>I will never ask for personally identifying information. Your Worker ID and IP address will not be included in any public releases of the study data.

<h2>Costs to You</h2>
<p>There are no foreseeable costs for you as a subject in this study.

<h2>Alternatives</h2>
<p>Your alternative to being in this study is to simply not participate.

<h2>Your Rights as a Research Subject</h2>
<ul>
<li>Your participation in this study is voluntary. You do not have to be in this study if you don't want to be.
<li>You have the right to change your mind and leave the study (by selecting "Return HIT") at any time without giving any reason, and without penalty.
<li>Any new information that may make you change your mind about being in this study will be given to you.
<li>You do not lose any of your legal rights by giving your consent.
</ul>

<h2>Questions About the Study or Your Rights as a Research Subject</h2>
<p>If you have any questions, concerns, or complaints about the study, you may <a href="https://arfer.net/elsewhere">contact me, Kodi Arfer, by email</a>.

<p style="margin-top: 2em;">If you type "I consent" below, it means that you have read (or have had read to you) the information given in this consent form, and you would like to be a volunteer in this study.
